Had an incredible time in Scotland celebrating Alex and Chelsie's wedding.  It was a beautiful weekend full of great times in an incredible location.  I managed to get myself up early on the last morning and go for a stroll around the grounds to soak it all in one last time...And to get my camera out.  I can tell it was a special time for me, as I didn't even think about my camera until right at the end (more often than not, photography is on my mind), choosing to be in the moment instead.  It also does help knowing there was a professional wedding photographer and videographer there too 🤣

A beautiful sunrise at Bamburgh Castle.  We added this stop to our short road trip after many recommendations to do so.  We stayed at a local bed and breakfast and took the short drive to the beach to see the castle at sunrise.  More photos to follow.

Same kind of shots but with changing light.

It's why I love shooting sunsets and sunrises, as each one is unique from one minute to the next.  Although it can also be quite overwhelming when you want to shoot everything and it changes none stop.

Interesting side note.  The new Indiana Jones movie filmed some scenes here.  I'm looking forward to seeing it to see how it is portrayed.

A couple more from our time in Bamburgh.  Quite surreal to see such an epic Castle nestled not only on a beautiful sandy beach but next to such a quaint town.

Lake District.  Where I fell in love with hiking and the outdoors in general growing up.
I had to bring Lydia along to see it while we were back.
Unfortunately, for there to be Lakes, there needs to be rain.  And that's all it did for the  2 days we visited.  Nevertheless we enjoyed our time outside in the rain, and inside, warm at many pubs and coffee shops.

Blue hour hit hard while we waited for the Galena Bay Ferry after a long soak at Nakusp Hot springs.  It was a great end to an amazing weekend away with friends new and old.  We did 2 nights, 3 days in a hut in Retallack, with some touring and xc skiing combined with lots of food and drink.  But I think my favourite time was sitting around the small table in the evenings, dimly lit by solar lights with the background sounds of the wood burning stove crackling away, while we played hours of  board and card games.  A weekend filled with laughter and good memories, is a weekend well spent.

Fresh snow and teasings of morning sun.  This is how most people in Revelstoke love to wake up on a Friday.

Mackenzie Ave.
The heart of Revelstoke.

In this photo you can see;
-CP train passing by
- band stand (live music every night in the Summer)
- City Hall (white art deco building on left of the Avenue.
-Mt. Macpherson at the back.
-The famous bear sculptures are just behind the trains sea containers infront of the band stand, on either side of the Avenue.

Much of Revelstokes downtown charm, stems from this Avenue.

Just above the dam in Lake Revelstoke I noticed some ice patterns and cool reflections as I drove by.  It was blue hour, and it lived up to its name.  A nice calm and quiet few minutes.  Until I fell waist deep in the snow bank that is.

It's also hard to see on instagram but there are a pair of birds floating together in the still waters.  Making the most of the calm winds.  That was a nice added touch.

Also, last two photos.  Same shot, different orientations.  It's kind of abstract so think it can work in a portrait setting.  What do you think?

S.W.I.P.E
Been doing quite a few panoramas lately.  All handheld with the long zoom lens.  A very amateur way of doing it.  But when I'm walking the dog and I often have a bag of poop in one hand, I don't want to be setting up tripods, especially in winter.  Aslong as Lightroom can stitch them together for me automatically and they are sharp then it's job done, in my opinion. 

If you're a canon shooter on a budget.  I'd recommend the RF100-400.  Been a stellar lens.  Sharp, light and compact.  And the close focus ability makes it very versatile.

We sat and watched an Osprey nest from our canoe for a while.  And then we heard some Geese.  Took us a while to spot them flying low across the lake, but finally locked on and to our surprise they were headed straight for the Osprey nest.  The Osprey took flight and one of the Geese landed.  The Osprey, I think, quickly remembered it was an Osprey.  Did a quick loop and dived back to reclaim its home.

A surreal few moments.  But a quick Google search revealed, it is not unheard of for Geese to try and steal Osprey nests.  I've personally never seen a Goose anywhere but on water or land.  Certainly not in a tree.  But there you go.

Had my mind blown a little.  Make sure you check out the last slide too for scale reference (not my image).
I spent the night sleeping up on a local mountain last week.
As the sun was setting the smokey air in the valley made looking and photographing the Sun very easy.
I took some photos and I often zoom in to make sure I mailed the focus.  But I noticed two black dots.  At first I was sure there was just dust on my sensor.  But when I reviewed other images, the black dots were moving with the Sun!
I did a quick Google and it turns out they are sunspots.  Cooler patches on the surface of the Sun where the magnetic field is stronger, which allows less heat to reach the surface, giving the appearance of Dark/black spots.  These are the source of solar flares and coronal mass ejections (CME's) which result in the potential of Northern and Southern lights when the particles reach Earth's atmosphere.

What's really mind blowing is these sunspots are much bigger than Earth!! The Sun is 109 times the diameter of Earth and 1,300,000 Earth's could fit inside the Sun.  Crazy.

Against the odds, and with a big thanks to @tooforeignforhome for texting me while walking the dog, that the sun was burning through the clouds.  I managed to capture a partial eclipse.  Earlier this morning the sky was fully blanketed with clouds and I just resigned myself to not being able to see the eclipse.  I didn't even think to check outside occasionally.  And for some silly reason, when Lydia text me, I panic got dressed and ran around like a headless chicken trying to figure out where I'd drive to for a photo.  Then as I left I remembered it was the Sun and I can just see it from the back Garden 🤣.

Thankfully years ago I purchased some ND filters.  That combined with a thin veil of clouds enabled me to expose a shot for both the eclipse and the clouds.

Panic over, eclipse captured, back to my coffee.

Have a good weekend 🤙

Little homage to The Big Eddy Bridge.  Pano at the end...As it seems that's something I enjoy lately.
Also, a little history for you.  The houses you see along the river edge are in the area known as Farwell.  This was originally the first settlement here in 1855 and Front St back then was a business mix of general stores, hotels, brothels and saloons.
When the railway finally arrived they didn't get along with Mr.Farwell, the original surveyor and land owner.  So they set up their rail yard east of his land.  Eventually in 1897 the battle for the name of the town was won by the railway and named after Lord Revelstoke, whose Banking firm was a big financial supplier to help finish the railway.

Now the weather has turned decidedly cold, and wet, and grey and.... miserable.  It has made me aware of two things.  I'm not ready for Winter both physically and mentally.  And that I have a huge backlog of photos to get through.  This is from Early September, arguably my favourite month of the year.  My parents visited and we went up Revelstoke National Park to the summit.  They took a selfie with the summit sign and a Whisky Jack photobombed them.  Impeccable timing, and a great memory.

I also found myself the other day, Ina daydream, excited for Spring.  Which is worrying, as we have around 5 months of the very definition of Winter between now and then.  I'll survive, just not sure I'll thrive, like many people do in this Winter mecca.

Anyway, I have more work on roofs to do and the cold has claimed my fingers multiple times already this past week.  So, Mother Nature, if you're reading this.  Can you just calm down with the Wintery stuff at least a few more weeks.  Thanks.

Cobweb season.  Lydia spotted this as we crossed the pedestrian bridge over the Illecillewaet River bridge on a recent walk. (Good luck pronouncing that, although it's just how it's spelt really).

As I took photos I wondered if the spider woke up and was annoyed by the dew.  Kind of like if you hang your laundry out and then it rains.  Or do they just climb on it and shake like a nutter to get it all off?

I enjoy cobwebs in situations like this.  When I can see them and admire their construction from a distance, really quite beautiful.  I'm not such a fan when I'm hiking or biking and my face becomes a cobweb magnet.  You can feel them, but they are difficult to get off.  You know when you get a hair in your mouth and you just can't get it.  Just like that, but over your face.  Anyway,  another spider related thought in this instance is why build your web across the trail to be smashed with someones face?  They spent all night working tirelessly for my ugly mug to come along and blindly decimate it in a split second.  I actually feel bad when I do and apologise.  Like it's just sitting in the bush in disbelief screaming "AGAIN?! WHAT THE ACTUAL F**K!". You just want to pull them aside and say "If you want your web to last a little longer, there are a lot of bushes and trees around here that aren't on trails you know?" Maybe it's a high fly traffic area too?  Who knows, they never answer when I ask.

It was a beautiful September/October.  This weather and colour feels so long ago now.  I'll just relive them through my images....And there's a lot of them!  Hopefully you enjoy them.  Apologies in advance if it just makes you miss that time of year already.  I know how you feel.

A short, sharp rain storm passed through at the end of my dog walk on the Greenbelt.  As I drove up the hill past the rec center I saw hints of light coming down Eagle Pass.  I've always liked that Pass.  Not only because highway 1 runs through it and gives us access to Costco 🤣 but more because it's that gap in the mountain range that lets us have light for just a little longer.  Especially in the Darker, winter months.  I'll take as much daylight as I can get.  The light shone bright for a while backlighting the beautiful fall colours.  Right place, right time.
